Click on the Browse button and find the image you want to use on your computer. Press "OK" in that window and then "Save" to return to your profile. Please try to optimize your image and make it as small and compact as you can. That way your profile will load much faster. Advance directives are written documents that describe the extent of the medical treatment you would desire should you become unable to make those decisions or communicate. One of these documents is known as a Living Will. Another common document records the name of the person who will decide on your medical care if you are unable to make those decisions. This document is called a Durable Power of Attorney for Health Care, or a Health Care Proxy. A Out of Hospital Resuscitation Order is document that tells emergency personnel not to perform CPR or resuscitate you before you get to the hospital if you are not able to tell them yourself. It will only be in effect outside the hospital. Once you arrive at a hospital, the Out of Hospital Resuscitation Order becomes ineffective. To fill this form out completely you first have to create your contacts in the 'Contacts' section before associating them with the advance directives.
Have you written your will already?
Choose the possessor of the Living Will. You have to have created this person as one of your "Contacts" before you can associate anyone to this field.

Type: Chickenpox (varicella) is a common childhood disease. It is usually mild, but it can be serious, especially in young infants and adults. Chickenpox causes a rash, itching, fever, and tiredness. It can lead to severe skin infection, scars, pneumonia, brain damage, or death. Gender: All Age: If you never had chickenpox and show a lack of immunity with lab testing, you should consider being vaccinated if you:
  • live in a household with young children
  • live or work in environments in which transmission of chickenpox is likely (e.g., teachers of young children, day-care employees, and residents and staff in institutional settings) or can occur (e.g., college students, inmates and staff of correctional institutions, and military personnel)
  • are a non-pregnant woman of childbearing age (to reduce the risk of transmitting the virus to the fetus if you become pregnant in the future)
  • are traveling overseas, because chickenpox is common in most countries
Frequency: Children between 1 and 12 years of age receive one shot. People who do not get the vaccine until they were age 13 or older should get two doses, 4-8 weeks apart. Precautions: The vaccine is not recommended for people with HIV/AIDS. You should not get the chickenpox vaccine if you have ever had a life-threatening allergic reaction to gelatin, the antibiotic neomycin, or a previous dose of the vaccine. Pregnant women should not be vaccinated, and women should not get pregnant for one month after getting the chickenpox vaccine. Check with your doctor about whether you should get the vaccine if you:
  • have a disease that affects the immune system, or are taking drugs that affect your immunity, such as steroids, for more than two weeks
  • have cancer, or are being treated with X-rays or drugs for cancer
  • find out from your doctor when you should be immunized if you recently received a transfusion or other blood products
  • if you are moderately or severely ill when you are scheduled to receive the shot, you should wait until your symptoms subside before being vaccinated
Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Diphtheria is an infection of the throat that can lead to breathing problems, paralysis, heart failure, and death. Tetanus is a potentially deadly illness that causes painful tightening of the muscles and locking of the jaw. Pertussis (Whooping cough) is a disease in children with the potential to produce a severe cough characterized by a 'whooping' sound.
The DTaP vaccine is a combined vaccine used to prevent the three diseases. It is given as a series of five shots, at 2 months, 4 months, 6 months, 15 to 18 months, and again at 4 to 6 years of age. It's important to receive booster doses of the diphtheria and tetanus vaccines every 10 years, starting at age 11 or 12.
Gender: All
Age: Children and adults; children should be assessed at ages 11-12 and immunized if they have not been immunized in the last 5 years.
Frequency: Every 10 years following your first series of three injections. However, if you have a dirty cut or wound, you may need a booster shot sooner (five years from your lastshot).
Precautions: Persons with a neurologic or severe hypersensitive reaction to a prior injection should avoid continued use of the vaccine. Some people get a sore arm or mild fever from the injection.
Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: The Hib vaccine is given to all children to prevent meningitis, bloodstream infections, arthritis, bone infections and other diseases caused by the bacteria Haemophilus influenzae type b (or Hib).
Gender: All
Age: Vaccination for children at 2, 4, 6 and 12 - 15 months of age.
Frequency: NA
Precautions: The vaccine has a safe track record and good antibody responses are found in patients with sickle cell disease, leukemia patients who have had splenectomies or who have HIV infection. There is no contraindication to giving these patients the vaccine.
Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Hepatitis A is a viral disease that attacks the liver, causing mild flu-like symptoms, jaundice, severe stomach pains and diarrhea. Gender: All Age: You should be vaccinated if you:
  • travel to, or work in, foreign countries that have high or intermediate rates of infection (Central or South America, the Caribbean, Mexico, Asia - excluding Japan, Africa, and southern or eastern Europe.)
  • live in communities with high rates of hepatitis A infection (American Indian, Alaska Native, and Pacific Islander communities, and some religious communities)
  • live in a community with a prolonged outbreak of hepatitis A infection. The hepatitis A vaccine is also recommended for all children living in areas of the United States where the incidence of hepatitis A virus infections is at least twice the national average. These states include Arizona, Alaska, Oregon, New Mexico, Utah, Washington, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Nevada, California, and Idaho
  • are a sexually active homosexual male
  • use illegal drugs
  • have a chronic liver disease
  • receive clotting-factor concentrates
  • work with infected primates or hepatitis A specimens in a research laboratory
Frequency: Two doses, with second dose 6-18 months after the first. The first dose should be administered at least one month before you travel overseas. Precautions: You should not have another dose of the vaccine if you received a serious allergic reaction to the previous dose. If you are moderately or severely ill on the day the shot is scheduled, wait until your symptoms have subsided before being vaccinated. Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Hepatitis B is a virus that can cause acute short-term symptoms, such as loss of appetite, diarrhea and vomiting, jaundice, pain in muscles, joints and stomach, and tiredness. It can also lead to liver failure and liver cancer. Gender: All Age: You should be vaccinated if you:
  • could be exposed at work to blood or blood-contaminated body fluids (healthcare personnel and public-safety employees, such as police officers and fire fighters)
  • are a client and staff member at an institution for the developmentally disabled, or a residential center (schools and workshops) attended by known hepatitis B carriers
  • are a dialysis patient
  • receive blood products for clotting disorders
  • are a sexual partner of a hepatitis B carrier, and live in the same household
  • are a family member of an adoptee from countries where hepatitis B infections are common
  • are a sexually active homosexual and bisexual man
  • are a heterosexual man or woman with multiple sexual partners, or were recently diagnosed with a sexually transmitted disease
  • abuse injectable drugs
  • plan to stay more than six months in a foreign country with high rates of hepatitis B infection
  • are a prison inmate
Frequency: Three doses (second dose 1-2 months after the first, and the final dose 4-6 months after the first) Precautions: The vaccine is made in baker's yeast, so people with a life-threatening allergic reaction to that substance, or to a previous dose of hepatitis B vaccine, should not be immunized. People who are moderately or severely ill at the time the shot is scheduled should wait until they recover before getting immunized. Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: The influenza virus can cause fever, sore throat, cough, headache, chills, and muscle aches. Most people are ill for several days, but some may need to behospitalized. Gender: All Age: For children 6 months to 8 years of age that are receiving the influenza vaccine for the first time, a series of two shots is administered, separated by one month. These groups (shown below) are recommended to receive the influenza vaccine every year:
  • children or adults with asthma or anyone living in the home of someone with asthma
  • children or adults with sickle cell disease
  • children or adults with other long-term diseases of the heart, kidney or lungs, or diabetes. Other members of the household should also be vaccinated
  • children or adults with weakened immunity from cancers (such as lymphoma or leukemia) or HIV infection
  • children on long-term aspirin therapy
  • women who are in their second or third trimester of pregnancy during the influenza season
  • adults over the age of 50
Frequency: Annually, usually in the fall Precautions: If you have a history of Guillain-Barre Syndrome, or have a serious allergic reaction to eggs, consult with your physician before deciding whether to get immunized. People who are moderately or severely ill on the day their shot is scheduled should not be vaccinated until their symptoms subside. Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Measles is a contagious disease that can lead to pneumonia, seizures, brain damage, and death. Mumps is a viral infection characterized by swelling of the salivary glands near the neck. It can lead to deafness, meningitis, painful swelling of the testicles or ovaries, and, rarely, death. Rubella is also known as German Measles. It is a virus that causes a rash, mild fever and arthritis (mostly in women). It can cause birth defects or miscarriage if a woman is infected during the first three months of her pregnancy. Gender: All Age: You should be vaccinated if you:
  • were born after 1956 without written proof of immunization on or after their first birthday, or a blood test documenting immunity to measles
  • are a healthcare worker born after 1956 (because of possible exposure to patients with measles)
  • are entering college or another post-high school educational institution
  • are traveling to foreign countries
Frequency: For children, the vaccine should be given as a series of two doses at 12 to 15 months of age and at 4 to 6 years of age. For people entering college, healthcare workers and travelers to foreign countries, two injections - with the second at least one month after the first - are necessary. Precautions: The vaccine is not recommended for HIV-infected persons with severe immunosuppression; persons with a life-threatening allergic reaction to gelatin, the antibiotic neomycin, or a previous dose of the vaccine. In addition, pregnant women should not be immunized, and women of childbearing age should avoid becoming pregnant for three months after the immunization. Talk to your doctor about whether you should be vaccinated if you:
  • have a disease that affects your immune system, or are taking drugs that affect your immunity, such as steroids, for more than two weeks
  • have cancer, or are being treated with X-rays or drugs for cancer
  • ever had a low platelet count. Find out from your doctor when you should be immunized if you recently received a transfusion or other blood products. If you are moderately or severely ill when you are scheduled to receive the shot, you should wait until your symptoms subside before being vaccinated
Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Meningitis is a potentially deadly inflammation of the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. The disease is usually caused by a viral or bacterial infection. Viral meningitis is relatively mild with fever and headache, but bacterial meningitis, if left untreated, can be fatal. Gender: All Age: The meningococcus vaccine is currently recommended for children over two years old at high risk of getting meningococcal infection. They are:
  • children and adults without a spleen
  • children and adults that lack a particular group of serum proteins that help the body fight infection (called complement proteins)
  • children and adults who will be traveling to sub-Saharan Africa from December through June
A single dose should also be considered for college students who live on campus as well as those children who may have come into contact with meningococcus Types A, C, Y or W-135 during anoutbreak. Education about the disease and the benefits of vaccination should be provided to incoming or current college freshmen, particularly those living in dormitories. Frequency: The vaccine is given in a single dose. Revaccination after 3 to 5 years for individuals at increased risk or during outbreaks should be considered. Precautions: Adverse reactions are usually mild, consisting primarily of pain and redness at the injection site for 1 or 2 days or fever. Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: NA Gender: All Age: Anyone over two years of age, with any of the following conditions:
  • are 65 and older
  • have kidney disease or kidney failure, HIV, heart, lung or sickle cell disease, diabetes, alcoholism, cirrhosis, leaks of cerebrospinal fluid, Hodgkin's disease, lymphoma; leukemia, bone marrow cancer, a damaged spleen or no spleen
  • have had an organ or bone marrow transplant, are undergoing long-term treatment with steroids, or radiation therapy for cancer
  • live in special environments in which the risk for pneumococcal disease or its complications is increased (Alaskan Natives and certain American Indian populations)
Frequency: Most people need one dose. Some people with certain medical conditions may require a second vaccination if the first dose was administered before age 65 and more than five years has elapsed. Precautions: Some people have a sore arm for one or two days following the injection. Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Pneumococcal infection is a serious illness in children, responsible for meningitis and death in children under 5 years old. Pneumococcal conjugate vaccine is approved for infants and toddlers. Protection lasts at least 3 years, so children who are vaccinated when they are infants will be protected when they are at greatest risk for serious disease. Some older children and adults may get a different vaccine called pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine. Please read the next entry in this list for the polysaccharide vaccine. Gender: All Age: Children under 2 years of age Frequency: A series of four injections beginning at ages:
  • 2 months
  • 4 months
  • 6 months
  • 12 - 15 months
Children who weren't vaccinated at these ages can still get the vaccine. The number of doses needed depends on the child's age. Ask your health care provider for details. Pneumococcal conjugate vaccine is also recommended for children between 2 and 5 years old who have not already gotten the vaccine and are at high risk of serious pneumococcal disease. This includes children who:
  • have sickle cell disease
  • have a damaged spleen or no spleen
  • have HIV/AIDS
  • have other diseases that affect the immune system, such as diabetes, cancer, or liver disease, or who take medications that affect the immune system, such as chemotherapy or steroids
  • have chronic heart or lung disease
The vaccine should be considered for other children who are at increased risk of serious pneumococcal disease. This includes children who:
  • are under 3 years of age
  • are of Alaska Native, American Indian or African American descent
  • attend group day care
The number of doses needed depends on the child's age. Ask your health care provider for more details. Precautions: Pneumococcal conjugate vaccine may be given at the same time as other vaccines. Some children should not get pneumococcal conjugate vaccine or should wait if they had a severe (life-threatening) allergic reaction to a previous dose of this vaccine, or have a severe allergy to a vaccine component. Tell your health-care provider if your child has ever had a severe reaction to any vaccine, or has any severe allergies. Children with minor illnesses, such as a cold, may be vaccinated. But children who are moderately or severely ill should usually wait until they recover before getting the vaccine. Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Polio is a virus that can cause paralysis and death by infecting the nerves of the body. The inactivated polio vaccine (IPV) is now the only vaccine given in the United States to prevent polio. It is given as a series of four shots, at 2 months, 4 months, 6 to 18 months and again at 4 to 6 years of age. Gender: All Age: Routine vaccination is not necessary for U.S. residents older than 18. The vaccine is recommended if you:
  • are traveling to countries where polio is common
  • work in a laboratory where you might handle specimens of the virus
  • are a healthcare worker treating patients who might have polio
  • are an unvaccinated adult whose children will be getting the oral polio vaccine
  • are a member of a community or specific population group with disease caused by 'wild' polio
Frequency: Adults in the high-risk groups who have never been vaccinated against polio should get three injections of the Inactivated Polio Vaccine (IPV):
  • the first at any time
  • the second 1-2 months later
  • the last 6-12 months after the second. High-risk adults who have had one or two doses of polio vaccine in the past should get the remaining one or two doses of IPV
Precautions: The oral vaccine is no longer recommended for use in the United States because of the slight risk (one out of 2.4 million) of contracting polio. Vaccination of pregnant women should be avoided. You should not get a polio shot if you have ever had a life-threatening allergic reaction to the antibiotics neomycin, streptomycin or polymyxin B, or a severe reaction to a previous dose of the vaccine. If you are moderately or severely ill when your vaccination is scheduled, you should wait until the symptoms subside before being vaccinated. Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Also known as German Measles, Rubella is a virus that causes a rash, mild fever and arthritis (mostly in women). It can cause birth defects or miscarriage if a woman is infected during the first three months of her pregnancy. Gender: All, but especially for women. Age: You should be vaccinated if you:
  • have no written proof that you were immunized on or after your first birthday, or a blood test showing immunity to rubella
  • are a healthcare worker who is at risk because of your exposure to patients with rubella, and who may have contact with pregnant patients
Frequency: One doze Precautions: The vaccine is not recommended for HIV-infected persons with severe immunosuppression; persons with a life-threatening allergic reaction to gelatin, the antibiotic neomycin, or a previous dose of the vaccine. In addition, pregnant women should not be immunized, and women of childbearing age should avoid becoming pregnant for three months after the immunization. Talk to your doctor about whether you should be vaccinated if you:
  • have a disease that affects your immune system, or are taking drugs that affect your immunity, such as steroids, for more than two weeks
  • have cancer, or are being treated with X-rays or drugs for cancer
  • ever had a low platelet count. Find out from your doctor when you should be immunized if you recently received a transfusion or other blood products. If you are moderately or severely ill when you are scheduled to receive the shot, you should wait until your symptoms subside before being vaccinated
Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Type: Diphtheria is an infection of the throat that can lead to breathing problems, paralysis, heart failure, and death. Tetanus is a potentially deadly illness that causes painful tightening of the muscles and locking of the jaw.
Gender: All
Age: Children and adults; children should be assessed at ages 11-12 and immunized if they have not been immunized in the last 5 years.
Frequency: Every 10 years following your first series of three injections. However, if you have a dirty cut or wound, you may need a booster shot sooner (five years from your lastshot).
Precautions: Persons with a neurologic or severe hypersensitive reaction to a prior injection should avoid continued use of the vaccine. Some people get a sore arm or mild fever from the injection.
Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Precautions: Persons with a neurologic or severe hypersensitive reaction to a prior injection should avoid continued use of the vaccine. Some people get a sore arm or mild fever from the injection.
Sources: Vaccine Information Statements and ACIP Statements, 2002. (Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

This field is necessary if a buyer orders more than one of this item. What will it cost you to ship 2 items instead of one? The multiplier is a fraction of the Domestic shipping cost. E.g. Shipping cost for one item = $10. Because of weight and dimensions it will cost you $12 to ship two items. The multiplier is then 0.2 of the shipping cost. So, for every extra item, the buyer will be charged $2 extra in shipping. If the buyer also buys multiple items from you, the system will use your highest shipping cost and its multiplier to calculate a total shipping cost.

A journal is a collection of patient data created by you from client medical history and over a series of appointments with the client. In order to start collecting data for your client you have to create a journal for the data to be stored. The fields you see to your left are all the fields you need to fill in to create a journal.

Anamnesis, or medical history, is the process in which physician obtains information about patient's health status by asking specific questions or by asking such questions of other people that know the person and can give suitable information (in this case, it is called heteroanamnesis). This kind of information, told by the patient, is called symptoms, in contrast to clinical signs, which are directly examined by the doctor.
Important: An anamnesis record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.
If you have any other remarks or comments for this journal that doesn't fit into the sections above, enter it here. Note: Comments are not time sensitive.

Examination entries are the result of a physician examining a patient for symptoms.
Important: An examination record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.

A conclusion is the result of a physician reviewing the patient's anamnesis, examinations and past and current diagnoses.
Important: An conclusion record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.

A note is a piece of information that pertains to the client's journal but does not fit into any other category.
Important: A note record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.

A referring diagnosis is the diagnosis usually given to the patient by patient's primary doctor.
Select the type of medical diagnosis standard you want to use by selecting it from the drop down. The next field will populate itself based on your selection. Further choose the topic and the results will display in the "Symptoms and treatments" area below.
Important: A diagnosis record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.

The referring professional is usually the patient's primary doctor and also the person who diagnosed her.
Important: A referring professional record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.

The professional diagnosis is where you give your patient diagnosis using one or more of the medical standards listed here.
Select the type of medical diagnosis standard you want to use by selecting it from the drop down. The next field will populate itself based on your selection. Further choose the topic and the results will display in the "Symptoms and treatments" area below.
Important: A diagnosis record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.

A treatment suggestion usually accompanies the referring diagnosis and is created by the patient's primary doctor.
Important: An anamnesis record is time-sensitive and will expire after 24 hours. That means you will not be able to edit or remove the entry; only set client access privileges.
